[2

Daily Telegraph, 21 April 1998
Delay on scheme to end British beef ban
By David Brown
THE Government's new computerised cattle tracking system based at
Workington, Cumbria, which aims to make British beef acceptable again in
Europe, will come on stream on Sept 28, eight months behind schedule, Jack
Cunningham, Minister of Agriculture, said yesterday.
The system will keep a record of the birth, movement and death of cattle,
and cost the taxpayer 35 million [British pounds to set up and run in its
first full year.
Although farmers' leaders and the Government have fulfilled all of Europe's
requirements to ensure the safety of British beef after the BSE outbreak and
to pave the way to a lifting of the export ban, they face strong resistance
until the computerised system is operational. The Agriculture Ministry said
the delay was due to the inclusion and enhancement of the current cattle
passport system, which is based on paperwork, in the new system. Ian
Gardiner, of the National Farmers' Union said: "It is all very frustrating".
